atreds but rather in a specific set of sociopolitical circumstances that occurred after the death of Tito and culminated at the end of the Cold War. In bringing together these essays, Serbian-born sociologist Jasminka Udovicki and Village Voice Washington correspondent James Ridgeway provide essential historical background for understanding the turmoil in Croatia, Bosnia, and Kosovo and expose the catalytic role played by the propaganda of a powerful few on all sides of what eventually became labeled an ethnic dispute.Burn This House offers a poignant, informative, and fully up-to-date explication of the continuing Balkan tragedy.Contributors. Sven Balas, Milan Milosevi´c Branka Prpa-Jovanovi´c, James Ridgeway, Stipe Sikavica, Ejub Stitkovac, Mirko Tepavac, Ivan Torov, Jasminka Udovicki, Susan Woodward   aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 12. Dez 2020) 7aHISTORY / Europe / General.2bisacsh1 aPrpa-Jovanović, Branka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aŠtitkovac, Ejub, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTorov, Ivan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRidgeway, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUdovički, Jasminka, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilošević, Milan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTepavac, Mirko, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRidgeway, James, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSikavica, Stipe, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWoodward, Susan L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBalas, Sven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aUdovicki, Jasminka, eeditor.